# Source of truth
- PROJECT_PLAN.md is authoritative. If anything you're about to do conflicts with it, or isn't covered
  by it, stop and ask rather than improvising a default.
- Section 3 of PROJECT_PLAN.md ("Non-Negotiable Design Decisions") overrides any "simpler" or more
  conventional CRUD pattern you'd normally reach for. Don't quietly simplify policy versioning,
  per-image verdict granularity, or the override/appeal split because it's less code.

# Before writing code
- Never assume a package is installed because it's common or you recall it from training. Run
  `npm list <package>` (or check package.json) before importing anything new. Install explicitly and
  say so if it's missing.
- For any new feature touching a domain entity, write the TypeScript interface/DTO and Mongoose schema
  changes first, in isolation, and show them before writing service/controller logic.

# What you may not do without asking first
- Don't modify `.env`, `.env.example`, `docker-compose.yml`, or `package.json` without flagging it
  explicitly and saying why.
- Don't add a new dependency unless the current task genuinely requires it.
- Don't commit or push. I review and commit myself, in small logical chunks.
- Don't delete or rewrite an existing file's logic wholesale when a targeted edit would do.

# Code hygiene
- No commented-out dead code left behind. No `console.log` debugging statements left in committed code.
- No swallowed errors — never catch an exception and continue silently. Either handle it meaningfully
  or let it propagate to the global exception filter.
- No `any` in TypeScript unless you explain why nothing more specific works.
- Be concise in explanations. Don't narrate standard NestJS/Next.js patterns I already know — flag
  only what's actually new, non-obvious, or a deviation from PROJECT_PLAN.md.
